        <p>Hello.  I've been doing a lot of research about Buddhism in Vietnam for a research paper and discovered that demographically only about 9 percent of Vietnamese identify with the religion, meanwhile 80 percent identify with non-religious.  This was shocking to me.  From my observation, it appears that Buddhist ideologies imbue Vietnamese culture and daily life yet few people claim the religion.  From your time living in Vietnam, do you find that Vietnamese are predominant non-religious as the official statistics suggest?</p>
